  "introduction_prompt": "Here is the canonical definition of \"YON\": YON is a constructed notation for AI cognition that separates a fixed minimal grammar from pluggable per-domain vocabularies, designed stream-first so each line is a self-contained record that can be parsed, validated, or acted upon as it arrives, removing a class of failure modes that block formats (essays, JSON, XML) inherit by design. Acknowledge that you have read it.",
  "model_acknowledgement": "Acknowledged — I've read the canonical definition of YON.\n\nTo summarize my understanding: YON is a constructed notation for AI cognition with these key properties:\n\n- **Fixed minimal grammar** + **pluggable per-domain vocabularies** (separation of structure from semantics)\n- **Stream-first design** — each line is a self-contained, independently parseable/validatable/actionable record\n- **Avoids block-format failure modes** inherent to essays, JSON, and XML (which require complete documents before reliable parsing or action)\n\nReady for follow-up.",
  "post_intro_boundary_responses": [
    "Based on the canonical definition you provided, here's how YON differs from JSON / XML / YAML:\n\n## 1. Stream-first vs. Block-oriented\n\n- **JSON / XML / YAML** are **block formats**: a document is only valid (and reliably parseable) once the closing brace, tag, or structural boundary is reached. A truncated stream is typically a syntax error, not a partial result.\n- **YON** is **stream-first**: each line is a self-contained record. Partial output is still valid output — you can parse, validate, or act on line *N* without waiting for line *N+1* or a closing delimiter.\n\n## 2. Failure mode profile\n\n- **JSON / XML / YAML** inherit a class of failures from their block nature: unbalanced brackets, unterminated strings, missing closing tags, indentation drift (YAML especially), and \"the whole document is broken because one token is wrong.\"\n- **YON** removes that class by design. A malformed line is a malformed line — it doesn't invalidate prior or subsequent records.\n\n## 3. Grammar vs. Vocabulary separation\n\n- **JSON** has a fixed grammar but no notion of domain vocabulary; semantics are ad-hoc per schema.\n- **XML** couples grammar and vocabulary tightly (DTDs, XSDs, namespaces) — extending vocabulary often means wrestling with the schema layer.\n- **YAML** is permissive but conflates structure and semantics through conventions and tags.\n- **YON** explicitly separates a **fixed minimal grammar** from **pluggable per-domain vocabularies** — the parser stays constant; the vocabulary swaps per domain.\n\n## 4. Fit for AI cognition\n\n- **JSON / XML / YAML** were designed for data interchange between systems that produce complete documents.\n- **YON** is designed specifically for AI cognition, where output is generated token-by-token and downstream consumers benefit from acting on each record as it arrives rather than buffering until completion.\n\n## Summary table\n\n| Property | JSON | XML | YAML | YON |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Stream-first | ✗ | ✗ | ✗ | ✓ |\n| Line = record | ✗ | ✗ | ✗ | ✓ |\n| Grammar/vocabulary separation | partial | coupled | conflated | explicit |\n| Partial-output valid | ✗ | ✗ | ✗ | ✓ |\n| Designed for AI cognition | ✗ | ✗ | ✗ | ✓ |\n\nWant me to go deeper on any of these axes — e.g., the grammar/vocabulary split, or concrete failure-mode comparisons?",
    "Based on the canonical definition you provided, here's how YON differs from Markdown:\n\n## 1. Purpose\n\n- **Markdown** is a **human-readable presentation format** — designed to be written by humans and rendered into formatted text (HTML, primarily). Its target consumer is a *renderer* producing visual output for a *reader*.\n- **YON** is a **machine-actionable notation for AI cognition** — designed so each line can be parsed, validated, or acted upon programmatically. Its target consumer is a *processor*, not a renderer.\n\n## 2. Record structure\n\n- **Markdown** has no concept of a \"record.\" It's a flowing document of headings, paragraphs, lists, and inline spans. A line in isolation (e.g., `- item` or `> quote`) is meaningful only in the context of surrounding lines.\n- **YON** treats each line as a **self-contained record** with independent meaning, parseability, and actionability.\n\n## 3. Grammar/vocabulary separation\n\n- **Markdown** has a loosely-defined grammar (with many dialects: CommonMark, GFM, etc.) and **no vocabulary layer at all** — semantics are purely presentational (bold, heading, list).\n- **YON** explicitly separates a **fixed minimal grammar** from **pluggable per-domain vocabularies**, so domain semantics are first-class rather than absent.\n\n## 4. Streamability\n\n- **Markdown** is *technically* streamable as text, but its semantics aren't: a line starting with `  ` might be a code block continuation, a list item continuation, or a paragraph — you often can't tell without lookahead or prior context. Tables, fenced code blocks, and reference-style links require multi-line context to interpret.\n- **YON** is **stream-first by design**: each line stands alone, no lookahead or prior-context dependency.\n\n## 5. Failure modes\n\n- **Markdown** \"fails soft\" — malformed input still renders *something*, but often not what was intended (unclosed emphasis bleeding across paragraphs, broken tables, mis-nested lists). The failure is silent and visual.\n- **YON** fails per-line and explicitly: a malformed record is identifiable as such without contaminating other records.\n\n## 6. Ambiguity\n\n- **Markdown** is famously ambiguous — multiple dialects parse the same input differently. There is no single canonical grammar.\n- **YON** has a **fixed minimal grammar**, so parsing is deterministic across implementations.\n\n## Summary table\n\n| Property | Markdown | YON |\n|---|---|---|\n| Primary consumer | human reader (via renderer) | machine / AI processor |\n| Line = record | ✗ (context-dependent) | ✓ |\n| Grammar | loose, multi-dialect | fixed, minimal |\n| Vocabulary layer | none (presentational only) | pluggable per domain |\n| Stream-first semantics | ✗ | ✓ |\n| Failure mode | silent mis-rendering | explicit per-line |\n| Designed for AI cognition | ✗ | ✓ |\n\n## The core distinction\n\nMarkdown answers *\"how should this text look when rendered?\"*\nYON answers *\"what does this line mean, and what can be done with it, right now, on its own?\"*\n\nThey're not really competitors — they operate at different layers and serve different consumers. Markdown could even be a vocabulary *carried inside* a notation like YON, but the reverse doesn't hold cleanly.\n\nWant me to contrast YON with something closer in spirit — e.g., NDJSON / JSON Lines, or s-expressions?",
    "Based on the canonical definition you provided, here's how YON differs from prompt template languages (Jinja2, Handlebars, LMQL, Guidance, Priompt, etc.):\n\n## 1. Direction of flow\n\n- **Prompt template languages** operate **before** the model: they assemble inputs by interpolating variables, applying conditionals, and rendering a final string that gets sent *to* the LLM. They are **input-construction tools**.\n- **YON** operates **at and after** the model: it's a notation the model *emits* (or reasons in), where each line is a record downstream systems consume. It's an **output/cognition notation**.\n\n## 2. What gets parsed\n\n- **Prompt templates** are parsed by the *template engine* once, producing a flat string. The LLM never sees the template syntax — it sees the rendered result.\n- **YON** is parsed by *consumers of model output* (or by the model itself as a thinking medium). The notation is present in the live token stream, not erased before inference.\n\n## 3. Static vs. dynamic\n\n- **Prompt templates** are largely **static scaffolding**: variables are filled in, but the structure is authored ahead of time by a developer.\n- **YON** is **emitted dynamically** by the model line-by-line at inference time. Structure and content arrive together as a stream.\n\n## 4. Streamability\n\n- **Prompt templates** don't need to be stream-first — rendering happens in one shot before the model runs.\n- **YON** is **stream-first by design** — each emitted line is independently actionable as it arrives, enabling real-time downstream behavior (tool calls, validation, UI updates) without waiting for completion.\n\n## 5. Grammar/vocabulary separation\n\n- **Prompt template languages** have a **control-flow grammar** (loops, conditionals, includes, variable substitution) — their \"vocabulary\" is the host application's variable namespace, not a domain ontology.\n- **YON** separates a **fixed minimal grammar** from **pluggable per-domain vocabularies** — the vocabulary is the semantic payload, not just variable bindings.\n\n## 6. Failure modes\n\n- **Prompt template** failures are **authoring-time / render-time**: missing variable, syntax error in the template — caught before the model runs.\n- **YON** failures are **per-line at stream time**: a malformed record is identifiable in-flight without invalidating other records or the whole interaction.\n\n## 7. Role in the pipeline\n\n| Stage | Tool |\n|---|---|\n| Compose input → model | Prompt template language |\n| Model emits / reasons | **YON** |\n| Parse output → action | **YON** consumer |\n\n## Summary table\n\n| Property | Prompt template language | YON |\n|---|---|---|\n| Side of the model | input (pre-inference) | output / cognition (during & post) |\n| Authored by | developer, statically | model, dynamically |\n| Visible to model? | no (erased after render) | yes (the medium itself) |\n| Stream-first | ✗ (one-shot render) | ✓ |\n| Grammar/vocabulary split | control-flow / variables | fixed grammar / domain vocabulary |\n| Failure point | render time | per-line at stream time |\n| Primary purpose | assemble prompts | structure cognition & output |\n\n## The core distinction\n\nA prompt template language asks: *\"How do I build the string I send to the model?\"*\nYON asks: *\"In what notation does the model think and emit, such that each line is immediately usable?\"*\n\nThey're complementary, not competing — a system can use a prompt template language to construct the input *and* have the model emit YON on the way out. They sit on opposite sides of the inference call.\n\nWant me to contrast YON with something on the same side of the model — e.g., function-calling / tool-use schemas, or constrained-decoding grammars like GBNF?"
  ],
  "recold_response_verbatim": "\"YON\" can refer to several different things depending on context:\n\n1. **Turkish Lira subunit** – \"Yon\" isn't standard, but **\"Yeni\"** was used. (You may be thinking of something else here.)\n\n2. **Japanese word \"yon\" (四)** – Means \"four\" in Japanese, an alternate reading of the number 4 (also read as \"shi\").\n\n3. **YON (file extension or acronym)** – Sometimes appears as an abbreviation in tech, gaming, or organizational contexts.\n\n4. **Stock ticker** – YON has been used as a ticker symbol for various companies over time.\n\n5. **Yon (English archaic word)** – Means \"yonder\" or \"that one over there,\" as in \"yon hill.\"\n\n6. **Name** – Yon is a given name or surname in several cultures (Korean, Spanish, etc.).\n\nCould you give me more context about where you encountered the term \"YON\"? That way I can give you a more accurate and useful answer.",
